 </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Syrian military commanders are meanwhile continuing to redeploy forces away from sensitive sites ahead of a postponed US air strike that many in Damascus believe is still likely.</p> <p>That's according to residents of the Syrian capital, who said today that troops had moved into schools and universities, which officials calculate are unlikely to be hit if Barack Obama orders an attack following a congressional vote next Monday.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/martin-chulov\">Martin Chulov,</a> in Beirut, and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alec-luhn\">Alec Luhn,</a> in Moscow, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syrian-forces-us-missile-targets\">report</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Damascenes reported more checkpoints than usual in regime-held areas, but said the capital continued to function as it had during the past two years of ever more entrenched war.</p> <p>In rebel-held districts, where siege and deprivation have bitten deeper, locals claimed a sense of despair had descended after Obama's speech.</p> <p>&quot;They were so close to doing something,&quot; said Umm Latifa, the widowed head of a household of six children in east Damascus.</p> <p>&quot;Anything to make [the regime] scared would have been a blessing.&quot;</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224ffbae4b03491b6ac8558\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T22:14:34.769+01:00\">10.14pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Some more now on those comments earlier by John McCain, a leading hawk on the issue of US military intervention in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/syria\">Syria</a>, who warned Congress that a &quot;no-vote&quot; next week against President Obama's plans for airstrikes would have &quot;catastrophic&quot; consequences that would weaken the US for years to come.</p> <p>The Guardian's Ed Pilkington <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/john-mccain-obama-syria-strikes-congress\">has filed a piece</a> on what McCain said, alongside fellow Republican senator Lindsey Graham, following their meeting with Obama.</p> <p>Asked by a reporter whether he intended to use his influence to convince other senators to back military action, McCain replied:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I am already talking to a lot of my colleagues, but before I can persuade them I have to be persuaded. The president made sense in a lot of things he said, but we are a long way from a coherent strategy.</p> </blockquote> <p>A direct question about whether McCain himself would vote in favour of the resolution authorising airstrikes, given his warnings about the catastrophic results of a &quot;no-vote&quot;, produced a less than definitive answer however.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>A weak response [to Syria] would give us a similar dilemma as that would also be catastrophic.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224fc4ce4b0c622abecf501\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T21:59:56.882+01:00\">9.59pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>David Kenner, Middle East Editor at Foreign Policy magazine, is among those who have been digesting that nine-page declassified French intelligence report on the Syrian government's alleged use of chemical weapons last month. He tweets:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/DavidKenner/statuses/374614752166961152\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>French intel can only confirm 281 deaths on Aug. 21, relying on social media videos. Far less than the U.S. death toll of 1,429.</p>— DavidKenner (@DavidKenner) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DavidKenner/statuses/374614752166961152\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>That's an apparent discrepancy at first glance, although Rosie Gray, a reporter for BuzzFeed Politics, makes the point below:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/RosieGray/statuses/374616267208282112\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/DavidKenner\">@DavidKenner</a> the report says they can confirm 280 just from videos but that their experts think the ~1500 number is likely valid</p>— Rosie Gray (@RosieGray) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/RosieGray/statuses/374616267208282112\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224f87ee4b0c622abecf500\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T21:43:42.408+01:00\">9.43pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Wadah Khanfar, a former director general of the al-Jazeera television network, argues (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/02/syrians-rid-assad-without-us-bombs\">in a piece for the Guardian</a>) that the Arab world has little trust in US motives regarding Syria and that an airstrike would not stop the slaughter of civilians.</p> <p>Instead, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/02/syrians-rid-assad-without-us-bombs\">he argues</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>What is now required is that the US and western countries allow Syrians to accomplish their revolutionary objectives by themselves – to eradicate the regime with their own hands.</p> <p>The west should not prevent them acquiring the means to decide the struggle militarily, and should encourage them to continue trying to build Syria according to the rules of real democracy, without excluding or marginalising any party or group.</p> <p>The Syrian people have proven their remarkable bravery in the struggle against tyranny; given the chance, I'm convinced they will demonstrate a similar level of responsibility in building a new democratic nation.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224ed9ae4b03491b6ac8550\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T20:57:14.714+01:00\">8.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">McCain: Plan emerging to 'upgrade' Syrian rebels</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>US senators John McCain and Lindsey Graham, Republican foreign policy hawks who have been pushing for a strong US response to last week's alleged chemical weapons attack by the Syrian regime, have said that President Obama must make a strong case if he wants to win congressional backing for military strikes.</p> <p>Speaking to reporters alongside Graham after a private meeting with Obama, McCain suggested that a plan was now emerging to &quot;ugrade&quot; the capability of the Free Syrian Army and &quot;degrade&quot; that of Assad but warned that an intervention now will be more difficult because Assad &quot;is moving his forces around.&quot;</p> <p>While he and Graham appeared to be somewhat encouraged by what they had been told by Obama, they were evasive on the question of fully backing his strategy.</p> <p>McCain said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I think it is encouraging but we have to have concrete plans, we have to have concrete details and assurances that this has moved on from the neglect of the last two years.</p> </blockquote> <p>Graham said that it was &quot;time for the Syrian opposition to step forward&quot; and provide some type of assurances about what its attitude would be to Syria's chemical weapons stocks in the event that it prevailed in the conflict.</p> <p>He also suggested that it was time for other states in the Middle East to take on board &quot;the lion's share&quot; in terms of the financial cost of backing the opposition to Assad.</p> <p>Both used the word &quot;catastrophic&quot; to describe the consequences of the US Congress rejecting Obama's plans.</p> <p>The reputation of the US would be &quot;shredded&quot;, said McCain who said that it would have implications not just for this presidency but also future ones in terms of its authority in the world.</p> <p>Graham added:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We urge the President to up his game and inform the American people what does it mean if Assad wins and the opposition loses.</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-f6784738-3c90-4eb0-9d6a-48febaaedbbc\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378151551015/41e20526-f6cd-4325-b630-26893c3ed74e-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Senators John McCain and Lindsey Graham speaking after meeting with President Barack Obama at the White House.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Senators John McCain and Lindsey Graham speaking after meeting with President Barack Obama at the White House. Photograph: MIKE THEILER/REUTERS</figcaption> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T20:59:24.751+01:00\">at 8.59pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5224df9ee4b03491b6ac8549\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T19:57:34.486+01:00\">7.57pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Bilal Abdul Kareem, a documentary filmmaker from New York who specializes in Muslim affairs and has filmed alongside Islamist fighters in Syria, has been talking to Channel 4 news.</p> <p>He says that those fighters believe that it was either Assad who launched a chemical attack in Syria last month, or &quot;someone within his regime who was complicit with foreign powers to launch that attack&quot;.</p> <p>The atmosphere is one of &quot;eager anticipation&quot; now he says, adding that the fighters he has been with believe there will be some level of attack on them as well.</p> <figure class=\"element element-embed\" data-canonical-url=\"\"> <object id=\"flashObj\" classid=\"clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000\" codebase=\"http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,47,0\" height=\"260\" width=\"370\"><param name=\"movie\" value=\"http://c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1\"></param><param name=\"bgcolor\" value=\"#FFFFFF\"></param><param name=\"flashVars\" value=\"videoId=2643708710001&amp;playerID=69900095001&amp;playerKey=AQ~~,AAAAAEabvr4~,Wtd2HT-p_VhJQ6tgdykx3j23oh1YN-2U&amp;domain=embed&amp;dynamicStreaming=true\"></param><param name=\"base\" value=\"http://admin.brightcove.com\"></param><param name=\"seamlesstabbing\" value=\"false\"></param><param name=\"allowFullScreen\" value=\"true\"></param><param name=\"swLiveConnect\" value=\"true\"></param><param name=\"allowScriptAccess\" value=\"always\"></param><embed src=\"http://c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1\" bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\" flashvars=\"videoId=2643708710001&amp;playerID=69900095001&amp;playerKey=AQ~~,AAAAAEabvr4~,Wtd2HT-p_VhJQ6tgdykx3j23oh1YN-2U&amp;domain=embed&amp;dynamicStreaming=true\" base=\"http://admin.brightcove.com\" name=\"flashObj\" seamlesstabbing=\"false\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" swliveconnect=\"true\" allowscriptaccess=\"always\" pluginspage=\"http://www.macromedia.com/shockwave/download/index.cgi?P1_Prod_Version=ShockwaveFlash\" height=\"260\" width=\"370\" /></object> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224d921e4b03491b6ac8546\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T19:29:53.514+01:00\">7.29pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">French PM: France aims to build coalition for Syria action</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The French Prime Minister, Jean-Marc Ayrault, says that France aims to build a coalition of countries to back military action against the Syrian government.</p> <p>In comments<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-french-intelligence-assad\"> after he presented French MPs with an intelligence report</a> on the Syrian regime's alleged use of chemical weapons, he said: </p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>This act cannot be left without a response. It's not for France to act alone.</p> <p>The president is continuing his work of persuasion to bring together a coalition without delay.</p> <p>France is determined to penalise the use of chemical weapons by (President Bashar al-)Assad's regime and to dissuade with a forceful and firm response.</p> <p>The objective is neither to topple the regime or liberate the country.</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-33a4cdaf-2fc8-4318-9321-668d46dc1146\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378146550555/3282fc8f-0d5d-43bb-8a29-7d5498340a98-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"French Prime minister Jean-Marc Ayrault makes a statement following a meeting with MPs focusing on the situation in Syria.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>French Prime minister Jean-Marc Ayrault makes a statement following a meeting with MPs focusing on the situation in Syria. Photograph: DEMARTHON/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224d662e4b0b6f34d589f67\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T19:18:10.825+01:00\">7.18pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The French intelligence report says that the Syrian chemical weapons programme began in the 1970s and states that Damascus has more than 1,000 tonnes of chemical agents making it &quot;one of the most important operational stocks in the world&quot;.</p> <p>It describes Syria's chemical arsenal as &quot;particularly massive and diverse&quot;, including Yperite, VX (one of the most toxic chemical agents known) and &quot;several hundred tonnes of sarin&quot;.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The sarin and the VX … are partly stocked in a binary form, that is to say kept in the form of two chemical products called precursors, that are mixed just before use.</p> <p>This technique and the associated procedures show a great knowledge of the technology of chemical weapons by the Syrian regime.</p> </blockquote> <p>It adds that the Syrian regime is capable of delivering its chemical weapons &quot;with a very large range of several thousand vectors.&quot;</p> <p>These, it says, include Scud C, Scud B, M500 missiles, bombs and artillery rockets with a range of up to 500km.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Certain missiles can carry up to several hundred litres of toxic agent.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T19:31:37.210+01:00\">at 7.31pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5224d1c1e4b0c622abecf4f0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T18:58:25.128+01:00\">6.58pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The French intelligence report adds that reports have suggested that the Syrians were looking at new ways of dispersing chemical weapons, reports Kim Willsher. </p> <p>It says:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Notably, since the beginning of the conflict, our intelligence confirms the regime's use of munitions carrying smaller amounts of chemical agents adapted for tactical use as they are more accurate and localised.</p> <p>We cannot rule out that these trials have also been conducted using other types of chemicals normally meant for civil use and employed at a lethal dose.</p> </blockquote> <p>Under the heading: The chain of command and the responsibilities, the report says the Syrian Centre for Scientific Research Study (CERS) is responsible for producing toxic agents for use in war, pinpointing &quot;Branch 450&quot; as being responsible for filling munitions with chemicals and also the security of sites where the chemical agents are stocked.</p> <p>This branch, the French report claims, is &quot;composed only of Alawite military personnel...distinguished by a high level of loyalty to the regime&quot;. It adds:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Bashar al Assad and certain influential members of his clan are the only ones permitted to give the order for the use of chemical weapons. The order is then transmitted to those responsible at the competent branches of the CERS.</p> <p>At the same time, the army chiefs of staff receive the order and decide on targets, the weapons and the toxic agents to put in them.</p> </blockquote> <p>The French report also claims the Syrian regime has used chemical weapons against areas held by opposition forces &quot;with the aim of taking territory or causing terror&quot; for several months.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p> The competent French services have recuperated biomedical samples (blood, urine), environmental samples (earth) and materials (munitions) taken from victims or sites of attacks on Saraqeb, the 29 April 2013, and Jobar, in mid April 2013. The analysis carried out confirms the use of sarin.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224d02fe4b0b6f34d589f65\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T18:51:44.099+01:00\">6.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.gouvernement.fr/sites/default/files/fichiers_joints/syrie_synthese_nationale_de_renseignement_declassifie_02_09_2013.pdf\">Here's a link </a>to the declassified French intelligence report on the Syrian government's alleged use of chemical weapons (en Fran&ccedil;ais).</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-b1db9432-905f-4af1-88f8-831d0ba0b42f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378148702968/d0f4b233-d562-4ba4-a967-a6d6bd51433c-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"The front page of today's French report on Syria's chemical weapons programme.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The front page of today's French report on Syria's chemical weapons programme. Photograph: THOMAS COEX/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T20:05:15.113+01:00\">at 8.05pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5224cdc3e4b074ec23392227\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T18:41:23.746+01:00\">6.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">French intelligence: &quot;Massive use of chemical agents&quot; in Syria</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>A French intelligence estimate alleges that the Syrian regime launched an attack August 21 involving &quot;massive use of chemical agents&quot; and could carry out other strikes of a similar nature in the future.</p> <p>Details of a French intelligence report, which was at published around 7pm French time by the French government, stated the information had come from &quot;France's own sources&quot; and was based on a detailed technical analysis of evidence supplemented by &quot;additional elements gathered in cooperation with our principle partners&quot;.</p> <p>The Guardian's Kim Willsher in Paris has been monitoring what has been put out by the French government. The report states:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Syria has one of the most important operational stocks of chemical weapons as part of an old and diversified programme that has been the subject of surveillance by the French (intelligence) services and those of our principle partners, for a long time. This programme is one of the primary threats in terms of the proliferation of arms of massive destruction...</p> <p>In its battles engaged against the opposition to the regime of President Assad, Damascus has already employed such arms, namely sarin, in limited attacks against its own population, particularly in April 2013.</p> <p>The analysis of information that we have today leads us to believe that the 21st August 2013 the Syrian regime launched an attack on certain areas of the Damascus suburbs held by opposition units, using a combination of conventional weapons and the massive use of chemical weapons.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224c9e6e4b03491b6ac853e\" class=\"block is-key-event\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T18:24:54.702+01:00\">6.24pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Assad: Strike on Syria could trigger regional war</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Syrian President, Bashar al-Assad, has scorned allegations that his forces were behind chemical attacks in Damascus last month and warned of the danger of &quot;a regional war&quot; in the Middle East if the US and France launch a military strike on Syria.</p> <p><a href=\"http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2013/09/02/01003-20130902ARTFIG00532-la-mise-en-garde-d-el-assad-a-la-france.php\">In an interview with the French daily</a>, Le Figaro, Assad said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Those who make accusations must show evidence. We have challenged the United States and France to come up with a single piece of proof. (Presidents) Obama and Hollande have been incapable of doing so.</p> <p>Anybody who contributes to the financial and military reinforcement of terrorists is the enemy of the Syrian people. If the policies of the French state are hostile to the Syrian people, the state will be their enemy.</p> <p>There will be repercussions, negative ones obviously, on French interests.</p> </blockquote> <p>This is <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BenQuinn75\">Ben Quinn </a>taking over the live blog now.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-0047ad5f-c175-425a-a661-2600b93218d3\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378156780918/29e5f03d-b915-4ec7-9aa8-27754a266cdf-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Syria's president Bashar al-Assad gestures during an interview with French daily Le Figaro in a picture  distributed by Syria's national news agency SANA.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Syria's president Bashar al-Assad gestures during an interview with French daily Le Figaro in a picture distributed by Syria's national news agency SANA. Photograph: SANA/REUTERS</figcaption> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T22:19:50.889+01:00\">at 10.19pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52248e24e4b074ec233921fb\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T15:04:44.498+01:00\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Here is a roundup of the main developments today.</p> <h2>Syria</h2> <p>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/world/obama-seeks-syria-support-from-former-foe-mccain-13273.html\"><strong>President Barack Obama is meeting Senator John&nbsp;</strong><strong><strong>McCain</strong></strong><strong>&nbsp;at</strong><strong>&nbsp;the White House today hoping his foe in the 2008 presidential election will help sell the idea of a US military intervention in&nbsp;</strong><strong><strong>Syria</strong></strong><strong>.</strong></a>&nbsp;The meeting is meant to address concerns of those who feel Obama is not doing enough to punish&nbsp;Syrian President Bashar Assad's government, which the US says was behind an attack in the Damascus suburbs last month that it claims included sarin gas&nbsp;and&nbsp;killed at least 1,429 civilians, more than 400 of whom were children. McCain is perhaps the loudest voice in US politics in favour of intervention on behalf of the Syrian rebels. Yesterday, he said that that the president should threaten to take out Assad, warning that &quot;pinprick&quot; cruise missile strikes are unlikely to have much effect. He also warned against the possibility of Congress defying the president.&nbsp;</p> <p>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-obama-meet-mccain-over-support-military-action-live?commentpage=1#block-5224796ce4b0c622abecf4c6\"><strong>Russia has warned that a planned Geneva&nbsp;peace conference to end the conflict in Syria could be put off &quot;forever&quot; if the US goes ahead with military action, as it was reported that Russia&nbsp;is sending a reconnaissance ship to the eastern Mediterranean</strong>.</a>&nbsp;Foreign minister Sergei Lavrov, who issued the warning about Geneva, also&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-obama-meet-mccain-over-support-military-action-live?commentpage=1#block-5224445de4b074ec233921c7\">described the evidence shown to Moscow by the US alleging&nbsp;that the Syrian regime was behind an alleged chemical weapons attack is &quot;absolutely unconvincing&quot;</a>&nbsp;and said that the US has refused to share some information, saying it is classified.</p> <p>•&nbsp;<strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-obama-meet-mccain-over-support-military-action-live?commentpage=1#block-5224959ee4b0b6f34d589f4a\">Russian members of parliament will urge the US Congress not to approve military strikes on Syria</a></strong>, the speaker of the upper house of parliament told President Vladimir Putin today. Putin responded by saying &quot;there's nothing better than open dialogue&quot;.&nbsp;</p> <p>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-obama-meet-mccain-over-support-military-action-live?commentpage=1#block-5224518de4b0b6f34d589f29\"><strong>The French prime minister Jean-Marc Ayrault is meeting heads of French parliament groups and opposition parties today to brief them on Syria, as president Francois Hollande faces pressure to follow the US and UK by seeking approval in parliament</strong></a>. Ayrault is expected to hand MPs the French intelligence dossier on Syria's chemical weapons, after both the US and UK earlier made public their own reports.</p> <p>• <strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-intervention-downing-street-vote\">David Cameron's spokesman has ruled out another vote in the UK parliament on possible military action in&nbsp;Syria</a></strong>&nbsp;as Downing Street officials played down the prospect of a diplomatic initiative on the two-year civil war being launched at the G20 summit in Saint Petersburg at the end of the week. He said:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Parliament has spoken. The government has absolutely no plans to go back to parliament. In response to the use of chemical weapons, the government made the case for a robust response. It put before the house the joint intelligence committee paper. The government made its case and parliament expressed its view. Parliament has made clear its will that there be no British involvement in military action and we will respect that.</p> </blockquote> <h2>Egypt</h2> <p>• <a href=\"http://bigstory.ap.org/article/egypt-judges-recommend-dissolving-brotherhood\"><strong>A judicial official says a panel of judges has recommended the dissolution of the Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's largest political group, from which ousted President Mohamed Morsi hails</strong></a>.&nbsp;The panel said today in a recommendation to Egypt's administrative court that the Brotherhood has operated in violation of the law.The recommendation isn't binding to the court, which holds its next hearing on 12 November. It appears however a step closer to banning the group, whose legality was disputed even before Morsi's ouster.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T15:05:16.959+01:00\">at 3.05pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52249aefe4b074ec23392208\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T15:04:31.628+01:00\">3.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Guardian's Middle East editor, <strong>Ian Black</strong>, has compiled a countdown to potential Syria strikes:September 3 UN secretary-general Ban ki-Moon to consult the non-permanent members of the UN security council.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p><strong>September 4</strong> French national assembly expected to debate the situation in Syria in an extraordinary session.</p> <p><strong>September 5-6</strong> G20 summit in St Petersburg. Barack Obama, Vladimir Putin, Ban ki-Moon, David Cameron, Francoise Hollande and Angela Merkel all to attend.</p> <p><strong>September 5</strong> Informal meeting of EU defence ministers in Vilnius, Lithuania.</p> <p><strong>September 9</strong> US Congress returns from recess. Debate and vote to be held “as soon as it comes back into session”. Obama has said he does not believe the law requires him to seek approval, but America will be “stronger” if he does.</p> <p><strong>September 13</strong> UN weapons inspectors originally expected to report on the August 21 Damascus chemical warfare attack. But the UN secretary-general has already asked that it be speeded up.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224968ce4b03491b6ac8527\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T14:45:48.307+01:00\">2.45pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/lrozen/status/374525070536093696\">Al-Monitor journalist Laura Rozen is not convinced</a> a proposed visit by Russian members of parliament to lobby Congress against military action will get a warm reception.&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/lrozen/statuses/374525070536093696\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>not held in high esteem by Congress RT <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCSteveR\">@BBCSteveR</a>: Looks like Russia's parliament will try to lobby US Congress v US mil action on Syria</p>— Laura Rozen (@lrozen) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/lrozen/statuses/374525070536093696\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224959ee4b0b6f34d589f4a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T14:41:50.765+01:00\">2.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/02/us-syria-conflict-russia-usa-idUSBRE9810D420130902\">Russian members of parliament will urge the US Congress not to approve military strikes on Syria</a>, the speaker of the upper house of parliament told President Vladimir Putin today.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>&nbsp;I think if we manage to establish a dialogue with our partners in the US Congress ... we could possibly better understand each other, and we hope that the US Congress will occupy a balanced position in the end and, without strong arguments in place ... will not support the proposal on use of force in Syria.</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCSteveR/status/374524495505018880\">Putin reportedly welcomed the idea.</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/BBCSteveR/statuses/374524495505018880\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Putin welcomes idea of a Russian parliamentary delegation going to US Congress to talk Syria: &quot;There's nothing better than open dialogue&quot;</p>— Steve Rosenberg (@BBCSteveR) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCSteveR/statuses/374524495505018880\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T14:46:08.714+01:00\">at 2.46pm BST</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-522494e0e4b0b6f34d589f48\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T14:38:40.414+01:00\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Vatican has waded once more into the debate on the Syria crisis, the Guardian's Rome correspondent, <strong>Lizzy Davies</strong>, reports.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>After Pope Francis's powerful appeal yesterday for the international community to avoid a military intervention in Syria, more strong words from the Vatican today.&nbsp;</p> <p>Monsignor Mario Toso, secretary of the pontifical council for justice and peace, has told Vatican Radio that an intervention risks spreading violence to other countries. &quot;The road to a resolution of Syria's problems cannot be that of armed intervention,&quot; he said.&nbsp;</p> <p>&quot;The conflict contains all the ingredients for a war of global dimensions to explode and, in any case, no-one would escape unharmed from a conflict and an experience of violence.&quot;&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-fdec9f58-e4ff-4b05-95ab-3ad143b5b83f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378129111478/83fdb20e-cfca-4639-aab2-dd811cc119c2-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Pope Francis holds his Sunday Angelus prayer from the window of his appartment at the Vatican, yesterday.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Pope Francis holds his Sunday Angelus prayer from the window of his appartment at the Vatican, yesterday. Photograph: Vincenzo Pinto/AFP/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-522490ffe4b074ec23392200\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T14:22:07.185+01:00\">2.22pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>President Obama will not be able to rely on House Republicans to pass his resolution authorising military force against Syria, <a href=\"http://washingtonexaminer.com/article/2535027\">the Washington Examiner reports</a>. It says:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Usually hawkish Republicans questioned Obama’s Syria strategy and the GOP’s rising isolationist wing suggested that no amount of cajoling would persuade them to authorize another Middle Eastern military intervention. Nevertheless, Republican sources said the resolution might still pass, possibly with significant GOP support, but only if Obama invests political capital on his side of the aisle and sways House Democrats.</p> <p>“Republicans will expect the president to round up a lot of Democratic votes and show that he’s committed to his own request,” said a GOP operative with relationships in Congress.</p> </blockquote> <p>But&nbsp;Representative Devin Nunes, a California Republican who has served on the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence for the past three years,&nbsp;told the Examiner it was a lost cause for the president:&nbsp;“I may be wrong, but I don’t think the votes are even close.”</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52248978e4b0c622abecf4ce\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T13:50:00.882+01:00\">1.50pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Nato secretary general, Anders Fogh Rasmussen, said today that a &quot;firm international response&quot; is needed to the use of chemical weapons in Syria. He told a news conference:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We believe that these unspeakable actions which claimed the lives of hundreds of men, women and children cannot be ignored.<br />I think there is an agreement that we need a firm international response in order to avoid that chemical attacks take place in the future. It would send, I would say, a dangerous signal to dictators all over the world if we stand idly by and don't react.</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/natosource/secretary-general-nato-will-not-take-part-in-syria-strike\">Rasmussen said on Friday that NATO has no plans to intervene&nbsp;in Syria</a>, which would require the approval of all 28 of its members, having pointed the finger of blame for the chemical weapons attack at the Assad regime. But&nbsp;<a href=\"https://twitter.com/AndersFoghR/status/374503921659555841\">he said today that he &quot;fully supports the decisions of individual allies&quot;.</a>&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AndersFoghR/statuses/374503446646247425\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23NATO&amp;src=hash\">#NATO</a>’s position on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Syria&amp;src=hash\">#Syria</a> is clear. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23CW&amp;src=hash\">#CW</a> attacks that claimed lives of 100s of men, women &amp; children cannot be ignored</p>— AndersFogh Rasmussen (@AndersFoghR) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AndersFoghR/statuses/374503446646247425\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AndersFoghR/statuses/374503921659555841\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>I fully support decisions of individual allies. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23NATO&amp;src=hash\">#NATO</a> is alliance of democracies. Democracy doesn’t weaken us but is source of our strength</p>— AndersFogh Rasmussen (@AndersFoghR) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AndersFoghR/statuses/374503921659555841\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/THE_47th/status/374507043484217344\">Syrian activist The_47th has summed up the frustration of many of Assad's opponents</a> in what appears to be a response to Rasmussen's comments.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/THE_47th/statuses/374507043484217344\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>More Syria related news. Breaking: another big shot world leader says the chemical massacre cannot be ignored, as it is being ignored.</p>— The 47th (@THE_47th) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/THE_47th/statuses/374507043484217344\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-522484dbe4b0c622abecf4cd\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T13:30:19.508+01:00\">1.30pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Seven in ten people believe MPs were right to reject UK military action in Syria, <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-23931479\">according to a&nbsp;poll commissioned by the BBC</a>.</p> <p>An almost identical percentage (72%) did not think the move would damage the UK-US relationship, with two thirds saying they did not care whether it did or not.</p> <p>ICM Research spoke to 1,000 adults in England, Scotland and Wales by telephone between Friday and Monday.</p> <p>A&nbsp;<a href=\"http://cdn.yougov.com/cumulus_uploads/document/t6hnxrxntm/YouGov-Sun-Results-130827-Syria.pdf\">YouGov poll of nearly 2,000 people on Wednesday suggested 50% were against a missile strike</a>, while 25% were in favour</p> <p>Meanwhile, a poll of nearly 2,000 people carried out by Opinium Research for the Guardian newspaper on Saturday<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/aug/31/poll-british-military-action-syria\">&nbsp;found 60% were opposed to British military action.</a></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52247b3be4b0c622abecf4c8\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T12:49:15.819+01:00\">12.49pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The EU has reiterated its calls for a peaceful solution to the conflict in Syria, while refusing to comment on the steps taken by Barack Obama. Michael Mann, spokesman for the EU'S foreign policy chief, Catherine Ashton, <a href=\"http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2331304&amp;Language=en\">is quoted by Kuna as saying</a>:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>We don't have any comments to make on the vote in the British parliament and the decision to put it to the vote in the US.&nbsp;This is a question for EU member states and the US respectively. It is an internal issue.<br />&quot;t is very important for us to emphasise that our line is unchanged. What we need ultimately is a political solution to the crisis in Syria. We need to get the parties back to a political approach soon and we need to help Syria get out of the crisis.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224796ce4b0c622abecf4c6\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T12:41:32.330+01:00\">12.41pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Russia has warned that a peace conference to end the conflict in Syria could be put off &quot;forever&quot; if the US goes ahead with military action.</p> <p>Foreign minister Sergei Lavrov warned that the planned discussions in Geneva would be disrupted by a US strike, <a href=\"http://news.sky.com/story/1136057/syria-russia-warns-us-against-military-strike\">Sky News reports</a>. He is quoted as saying:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>If the action announced by the US President - to the great regret of all of us - does in fact take place ... it will put off the chances of (holding) this conference for a long time, if not forever.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52247781e4b0b6f34d589f3b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T12:33:21.902+01:00\">12.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/AviMayer/status/374475934960988160\">Israeli newspaper Israel Hayom is unimpressed by Obama's stance on Syria.</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AviMayer/statuses/374475934960988160\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Cartoon from Israel Hayom: &quot;Stop or I'll shoot! ...in a week or so... or two weeks... or a month...&quot; <a href=\"http://t.co/0KJ0vOhDWL\">pic.twitter.com/0KJ0vOhDWL</a></p>— Avi Mayer (@AviMayer) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AviMayer/statuses/374475934960988160\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>On the other side of the coin, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/exiledsurfer/status/374444253243387904\">this image of Obama,</a> draws inspiration from <a href=\"http://www.artrepublic.com/articles/8-the-peter-kennard-print-downing-st-tried-to-ban-now-at-artrepublic.html\">the famous Peter Kennard print of Tony Blair</a> that Downing Street reportedly tried to ban.</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/exiledsurfer/statuses/374444253243387904\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>&quot;<a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Obomber&amp;src=hash\">#Obomber</a> doing a selfie&quot; by <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jimicrackles\">@jimicrackles</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/UsJeIARdgb\">pic.twitter.com/UsJeIARdgb</a></p>— exiledsurfer (@exiledsurfer) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/exiledsurfer/statuses/374444253243387904\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224742de4b074ec233921ea\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T12:19:09.932+01:00\">12.19pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/5167c90ce4b06bae4b7cdb93/512660%20\">Here is a photo of a young Syrian refugee that arrived via Guardian Witness.</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-witness element-witness-image\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ImageObject\" data-media-id=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/5167c90ce4b06bae4b7cdb93/512660\"> <div class=\"element-witness--main\"> <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/5167c90ce4b06bae4b7cdb93/512660\" itemprop=\"url\"><img src=\"https://n0tice-static.s3.amazonaws.com/images/reports/microblogs/mediumoriginalaspectdouble/1378047613923e50bdf42132becb534d386bb50613679.jpg\" alt=\"New Arrival\" itemprop=\"contentURL\" /></a> <figcaption> <h3 class=\"element-witness--title\" itemprop=\"name\"><a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/assignment/5167c90ce4b06bae4b7cdb93/512660\" itemprop=\"url\">New Arrival</a></h3> <div itemprop=\"description\"> <p>This 3-year-old girl arrived to Za'atri last night with seven members of her family. The group had lived in and around Homs where they slept in one school and then another. Each time they returned to their home village there was bombing and fighting. Finally they fled to Jordan petrified for their past and afraid for their future.</p> </div> </figcaption> </div> <footer class=\"element-witness--footer\"> <p class=\"element-witness--source\">Sent via <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/\" class=\"element-witness--brand\" itemprop=\"provider\">GuardianWitness</a></p> <div class=\"element-witness--metadata\"> <p class=\"element-witness--author\" itemprop=\"author\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Person\"> By <a href=\"https://witness.theguardian.com/user/GregBeals\" class=\"element-witness--author-name\" itemprop=\"name\">GregBeals</a> </p> <p class=\"element-witness--date\"> <time itemprop=\"dateCreated\" datetime=\"2013-09-01T15:00:17Z\">1 September 2013, 16:00</time> </p> </div> </footer> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-522471d8e4b03491b6ac850c\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T12:09:12.593+01:00\">12.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Syria's state news agency has more details on the mortars that landed in central Damascus this morning, which <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-obama-meet-mccain-over-support-military-action-live?commentpage=1#block-52244687e4b03491b6ac84f0\">the Wall Street Journal's Sam Dagher tweeted</a> about earlier.<a href=\"http://sana.sy/eng/337/2013/09/02/500424.htm\"> Sana says</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Terrorists on Monday fired a rocket shell on a residential building near al-Jahez park in Abu Remmaneh neighborhood, Damascus, causing material damage.</p> <p>An official source told Sana that the terrorist attack caused material damage to the cars parking in the place as well as fire was erupted at the fifth floor of a residential building, but no casualties were reported.</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-c1a849d4-da30-464a-b936-bcf79f681e4d\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378120143115/0189d37e-68e6-41b1-a850-e6c6f5b498d9-bestSizeAvailable.jpeg\" alt=\"Apartment block hit by mortar in central Damascus\" width=\"375\" height=\"225\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>An apartment block was hit by a mortar in central Damascus, near where President Assad works and lives Photograph: /Screengrab from Sana</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52246f78e4b0c622abecf4bf\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T11:59:04.779+01:00\">11.59am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://beta.syriadeeply.org/2013/09/syria-rebels-hit-hard/#.UiRrwrvhEt2\">Syria Deeply has been speaking to rebel commanders about the prospects of western intervention</a>. Abdel Jabbar Okaidi, the FSA’s chief for Aleppo province, said that a weak campaign could do more harm than good:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>“If the strikes target the airports, Scud missile launchers, and command and control headquarters, then they will cripple the regime,” he tells Syria Deeply.</p> <p>On the other hand, “a light strike would be worse than doing nothing. If it’s not the death blow, this game helps the regime even more. The Syrian people will only suffer more death and devastation when the regime retaliates.”</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52246a8ce4b0c622abecf4ba\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T11:38:04.277+01:00\">11.38am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Petition2Congress website, which sends emails to Congress has separate petitions in favour of and opposed to military intervention in Syria. The pro-strikes one<a href=\"http://www.petition2congress.com/4360/stop-killing-in-syria/\">&nbsp;has sent more than 6,200 letters and emails to Congress so far</a>. It says:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>To: Congress and President Obama</p> <p>Please do not stand by and let Bashar Al-Assad kill the people of Syria for merely trying to voice their request for democracy, as many countries have done successfully.&nbsp;</p> <p>By signing this petition you are urging the Congress and President Obama to intervene, and to do the best they can to stop Bashar Al-Assad from killing civilians in Syria. Medical Aid is requested, as is media coverage in Syria. Assad will massacre the masses if we remain silent.&nbsp;</p> <p>Please act quickly, time is of the essence.</p> </blockquote> <p><a href=\"http://www.petition2congress.com/11311/say-no-to-bombing-syria/\">The one against military action has sent more than 660 letters and emails to Congress</a>, although it has been up for a much shorter period of time. It says:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>- The American People have spoken. The latest polls show more than 50% are opposed to any military action in Syria.<br />- Our closest ally, Britain has also rejected military intervention in Syria.<br />- Syria is not an imminent threat to the USA and has not attacked any of the USA allies in the Middle East.<br />- Attacking Syria without a UN resolution and without any aggression against our nation is [a] flagrant violation of international law.<br />- Our government is in debt and military action will further add to the financial drain.<br />- Attacking Syria in the midst of the instability of the civil war may provoke unpredictable responses and ignite a much wider regional war forcing the United States into an open ended conflict in the midst of a very fragile economic recovery.<br />- Al-Qaida is well established in Syria and weakening the central government will only further al-Qaida's objective in toppling Assad at this stage.<br />- Remember, you are in Washington to represent the people of the United States and the people have spoken loud and clear. &quot;No to starting a war in Syria&quot;!</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52246798e4b0b6f34d589f35\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T11:25:28.365+01:00\">11.25am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://bigstory.ap.org/article/pope-announces-day-fasting-prayer-syria\">The pope made an impassioned plea yesterday for the&nbsp;the international community to seek to solve the Syria crisis by peaceful means</a>.</p> <p>He seems to be<a href=\"https://twitter.com/Pontifex/status/374466943312330753\"> hammering the point home today.&nbsp;</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/Pontifex/statuses/374466943312330753\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>War never again! Never again war!</p>— Pope Francis (@Pontifex) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/Pontifex/statuses/374466943312330753\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-522463fce4b03491b6ac84ff\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T11:10:04.583+01:00\">11.10am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Hezbollah will fire rockets at Israel from Homs, in Syria, rather than from Lebanon, if there are strikes against the Assad regime, <a href=\"http://m.naharnet.com/stories/en/96463\">Lebanese website Naharnet reports</a>.</p> <p>The report quotes a source as saying the intention would be to avoid embroiling Lebanon in any military action taken by the Shia group, which has sent guerillas to fight alongside government forces in Syria.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52245e65e4b0b6f34d589f31\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T10:46:13.924+01:00\">10.46am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://bigstory.ap.org/article/un-7-million-syrians-displaced-civil-war\">The head of the UN refugee agency in Syria says 7 million Syrians, or almost one-third of the population, have been displaced by the country's civil war.</a></p> <p><a href=\"http://bigstory.ap.org/article/un-7-million-syrians-displaced-civil-war\">Tarik Kurdi told The Associated Press that 5 million of the displaced are still in Syria while about 2 million have fled to neighboring countries. He says 2 million children are among those directly affected by the war.</a></p> <p>Kurdi said UN assistance has been a &quot;drop in the sea of humanitarian need&quot; and that the funding gap is &quot;very, very wide&quot;. International donors have sent less than one-third of the money needed to help those displaced by the war, he said.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-1ee040e9-988f-45ba-b43e-e760ec26a82a\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378114638268/b88ffa39-cb54-43f7-a484-d8f93eb8e9dd-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Syrian refugees sit near a Turkish soldier on patrol at the Cilvegozu gate border with Syria..\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Syrian refugees sit near a Turkish soldier on patrol at the Cilvegozu gate border with Syria, on Monday 2 September, 2013. Photograph: Gregorio Borgia/AP</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224589de4b0c622abecf4b3\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T10:31:21.174+01:00\">10.31am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ow1rGbJYh-A\">Mortars have hit the Malki district of Damascus</a>, near where Assad works and lives.&nbsp;</p> <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ow1rGbJYh-A\"> <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"345\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/ow1rGbJYh-A?wmode=opaque&amp;feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe> </figure> <p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/status/374454707311620096\">The Wall Street Journal's Sam Dagher tweeted that an apartment was hit</a>. It was probably fired by rebels, he said (presumably because of the location).</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/statuses/374454707311620096\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Mortars most likely fired by rebels in <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Damascus&amp;src=hash\">#Damascus</a> suburbs hit apartment on west side of city, apartment on fire &amp; facade damaged <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Syria&amp;src=hash\">#Syria</a></p>— Sam Dagher (@samdagher) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/statuses/374454707311620096\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/statuses/374455120437981184\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>People saying owners of apartment just hit with mortars are away so not clear if there are casualties <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Damascus&amp;src=hash\">#Damascus</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Syria&amp;src=hash\">#Syria</a></p>— Sam Dagher (@samdagher) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/statuses/374455120437981184\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52245642e4b0b6f34d589f2e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T10:11:30.999+01:00\">10.11am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>&nbsp;Russia&nbsp;is sending a reconnaissance ship to the eastern Mediterranean, Interfax news agency reported today. <a href=\"http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/02/us-syria-conflict-russia-ships-idUSBRE98104O20130902\">From Reuters:</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The reconnaissance ship Priazovye left Russia's naval base in the Ukrainian Black Sea port of Sevastopol late on Sunday on a mission &quot;to gather current information in the area of the escalating conflict,&quot; the report quoted an unidentified military source as saying.</p> <p>The defence ministry declined immediate comment ...</p> <p>Interfax said the Priazovye would be operating separately from a navy unit permanently stationed in the Mediterranean in a deployment which President Vladimir Putin said is needed to protect national security interests.</p> <p>The defence ministry said last week that new warships would be sent to the Mediterranean to replace others in a long-planned rotation of the ships based there.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224518de4b0b6f34d589f29\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T09:51:25.243+01:00\">9.51am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>More from France, where Angelique says Hollande <em>is</em> planning to follow in the footsteps of Cameron and Obama today, at least in one respect:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The French prime minister Jean-Marc Ayrault will meet heads of French parliament groups and opposition parties late this afternoon to brief them on Syria. He is also expected to hand them the French intelligence dossier on Syria's chemical weapons, after both the US and UK earlier made public their own reports.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52244f8be4b074ec233921d2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T09:42:51.241+01:00\">9.42am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Guardian's Paris correspondent, <strong>Angelique Chrisafis</strong>, writes that Francois Hollande is still facing pressure to follow in the footsteps of David Cameron and Barack Obama.&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>In France today, pressure continues to mount on Francois Hollande who is now the only western leader to not call a parliament vote on military action. With the French constitution granting vast powers to the president, Hollande is not obliged to consult parliament before a strike. MPs will debate the issue on Wednesday afternoon but not vote on it. But more opposition voices, and even some in the Socialist party and Green party, have today been demanding a vote.</p> <p>&quot;Can Hollande be the only head of state to use force without a parliament vote, without even a speech?&quot; <a href=\"http://www.liberation.fr/monde/2013/09/01/douteux_928718\">asked the left-wing daily Lib&eacute;ration in an editorial</a>.</p> <p>Elisabeth Guigou, Socialist head of the parliament's foreign affairs committee, told France Info radio: &quot;In a complicated situation like this, we need to stick to principles, in other words the constitution, which does not oblige the president to hold a vote, nor even a debate.”</p> <p>&quot;I don't see that holding a vote would make any sense politically,&quot; she said, noting France would be left in an impossible situation were parliament to vote in favour of action and then the US Congress to vote against.</p> <p>She said France maintained it was important to act on chemical weapons in Syria. &quot;France cannot act alone. To give an intervention legality it would need to be carried out by a broad coalition,&quot; she said.&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52244c58e4b03491b6ac84f2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T09:29:12.586+01:00\">9.29am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>China said today that, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/02/syria-crisis-obama-meet-mccain-over-support-military-action-live#block-5224445de4b074ec233921c7\">like Russia</a>, it has been briefed by the United States about evidence on the use of chemical weapons in Syria, as it expressed concern about plans for unilateral military action. <a href=\"http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/09/02/us-syria-crisis-china-idUSBRE98104820130902\">From Reuters:</a></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>&quot;The US side briefed China on what evidence the US had in relation to the use of chemical weapons by the relevant party in Syria as well as the relevant decision by the United States,&quot; China's foreign ministry spokesman, Hong Lei, told a daily news briefing.&nbsp;</p> <p>He did not elaborate on what China thought of the evidence it had been shown ...&nbsp;</p> <p>Hong repeated that China opposed the use of chemical weapons by any side and that China supported the independent, objective investigation by the UN experts.&nbsp;<br />&quot;China expressed serious concern about preparations by relevant countries for unilateral military action,&quot; Hong said.&nbsp;<br />&quot;Any action by the international community ought to respect the rules of the UN charter and basic norms of international relations and avoid further complicating the Syria issue and avoid further disaster for the Middle East.&quot;&nbsp;</p> <p>Russia and China have both vetoed previous Western efforts to impose UN penalties on Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.</p> <p>But China has been keen to show it is not taking sides and has urged the Syrian government to talk to the opposition and take steps to meet demands for political change. It has said a transitional government should be formed.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52244687e4b03491b6ac84f0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T09:04:23.874+01:00\">9.04am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/status/374425509398315009\">This photo shows an Assad supporter making her feelings clear at a rally in New York.</a></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/statuses/374425509398315009\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Syria&amp;src=hash\">#Syria</a> army boot RT “<a href=\"https://twitter.com/omarsyria\">@omarsyria</a>: Assad supporter at NYC rally resists Western hegemony by putting mil boot on head <a href=\"http://t.co/XnpGTEokKz\">pic.twitter.com/XnpGTEokKz</a>”</p>— Sam Dagher (@samdagher) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/samdagher/statuses/374425509398315009\">September 2, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5224445de4b074ec233921c7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T08:55:09.122+01:00\">8.55am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Russian foreign minister Sergei Lavrov said today that the information the US showed Moscow trying to prove that the Syrian regime was behind an alleged chemical weapons attack is &quot;absolutely unconvincing.&quot;</p> <p>Lavrov said &quot;there was nothing specific&quot; in the evidence presented by Washington, &quot;no geographic coordinates, no names, no proof that the tests were carried out by the professionals&quot;. He did not say what tests he was referring to.</p> <p>Lavrov added that US officials told Russia they cannot share all the evidence because some of it is classified.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52243f49e4b0b6f34d589f20\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T08:33:29.714+01:00\">8.33am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The Syrian Electronic Army,<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media-network/partner-zone-infosecurity/what-is-the-syrian-electronic-army\"> a group of political hacktivists working in support of Syrian President Bashar al-Assad</a>, has hacked into <a href=\"http://marines.com/\">a website of the US Marines</a>.</p> <p>The tone of the message is interesting, describing the Marines as their &quot;brothers&quot;, appealing rather than threatening or ridiculing. It says:&nbsp;</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>This is a message written by your brothers in the Syrian Army, who have been fighting al-Qaida for the last 3 years.</p> <p>We understand your patriotism and love for your country so please understand our love for ours.</p> <p>Obama is a traitor who wants to put your lives in danger to rescue al- Qaida insurgents.</p> <p>Marines, please take a look at what your comrades think about Obama's alliance with al-Qaida against Syria.&nbsp;</p> <p>&nbsp;Your officer in charge probably has no qualms about sending you to die against soldiers just like you,&nbsp;fighting a vile common enemy. The Syrian army should be your ally not your enemy.</p> <p>Refuse your orders and concentrate on the real reason every soldier joins their military, to defend their homeland.&nbsp;</p> <p>You're more than welcome to fight alongside our army rather than against it.&nbsp;</p> <p>Your brothers, the Syrian army soldiers. A message delivered by the SEA&nbsp;</p> </blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-29e4336e-d17a-4887-9cd7-9f6818030bc7\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/9/2/1378107117465/6fd6b447-00be-4211-9afb-73f4a70c6f71-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Marines website hacked by Syrian Electronic Army\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The Syrian Electronic Army has hacked into a website of the US Marines Photograph: /Screengrab from marines.com</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52243c51e4b0c622abecf4a0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T08:20:49.570+01:00\">8.20am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/09/01/the-5-ways-that-congress-is-splitting-on-syria/?hpid=z2\">The Washington Post says that very few members of Congress have said whether they will vote for or against military action</a> because they are waiting to see how the Obama administration makes its case.&nbsp;</p> <p>It says they are currently split into the following five groups.</p> <p>•&nbsp;The “do it now, already” caucus</p> <p>•&nbsp;The “want bigger military action” caucus (including John McCain)</p> <p>•&nbsp;The “happy to debate the issue, reserving judgment” caucus (this is the largest group, according to the Post)</p> <p>• The sceptical caucus</p> <p>• The anti-military action caucus</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52243835e4b0b6f34d589f1d\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-09-02T08:03:17.686+01:00\">8.03am <span class=\"timezone\">BST</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Good morning. Welcome to Middle East Live.</p> <p>Here is a roundup of the latest developments.</p> <h2>Syria</h2> <p>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.indiatvnews.com/news/world/obama-seeks-syria-support-from-former-foe-mccain-13273.html\"><strong>President Barack Obama is meeting Senator John&nbsp;</strong><strong><strong>McCain</strong></strong><strong> at</strong><strong> the White House, today hoping his foe in the 2008 presidential election will help sell the idea of a US military intervention in&nbsp;</strong><strong><strong>Syria</strong></strong><strong>&nbsp;.</strong></a> The meeting is meant to address concerns of those who feel Obama is not doing enough to punish&nbsp;Syrian President Bashar Assad's government, which the US says was behind an attack in the Damascus suburbs last month that it claims included sarin gas&nbsp;and&nbsp;killed at least 1,429 civilians, more than 400 of whom were children. McCain is perhaps the loudest voice in US politics in favour of intervention on behalf of the Syrian rebels. Yesterday, he said that that the president should threaten to take out Assad, warning that &quot;pinprick&quot; cruise missile strikes are unlikely to have much effect. He also warned against the possibility of Congress defying the president.&nbsp;</p> <p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/01/us-members-congress-syria-briefing\"><strong>After a</strong><strong> classified briefing was held on Capitol Hill yesterday, </strong><strong>it was clear that the Obama administration could not be sure of the outcome of the vote on military action.</strong></a> In particular, Obama could not count on his own party to deliver the votes. &quot;I don't know if every member of Congress is there yet,&quot; said Representative Janice Hahn, a California Democrat who said she would vote no on authorising a military strike. &quot;The room was sceptical,&quot; said Jim Himes, a Connecticut Democrat.</p> <p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/01/obama-strike-syria-congress-kerry\"><strong>The US secretary of state, John Kerry, expressed confidence that Congress would back Obama but said the president could go ahead with military strikes even without its approval.</strong></a>&nbsp;&quot;We don't contemplate that the Congress is going to vote no,&quot; Kerry said, but he stressed the president had the right to take action &quot;no matter what Congress does&quot;.</p> <p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/02/ministers-face-questions-chemicals-syria\"><strong>British ministers are to face further questions over the decision to allow the export of substances used to make&nbsp;</strong><strong>chemical weapons</strong><strong>&nbsp;to&nbsp;</strong><strong>Syria</strong><strong>, months after the country descended into civil war. </strong></a>In a letter to the business secretary,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/vincentcable\">Vince Cable</a>, to be sent on Monday, a member of the House of Commons' committee on arms export controls will demand to know who was allowed to sell the chemicals and what other licences for the export of dangerous materials to Syria have been granted.</p> <p>•&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10279620/Pressure-on-Cameron-for-new-vote-on-Syria-strikes.html\"><strong>David Cameron is under increasing pressure to return to parliament for another vote on British military action against Syria after the US postponed missile strikes for at least a week, the Daily Telegraph writes.&nbsp;</strong></a>Lord Howard, a former Conservative leader, Sir Malcolm Rifkind, a former foreign secretary, and Lord Ashdown, a former Liberal Democrat leader, yesterday led calls to vote again. The London mayor, and potential future Tory leader, <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10279546/The-delayed-attack-on-Syria-is-good-for-Britain-and-the-PM.html\">Boris Johnson, writes in the Telegraph</a>:</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>If there is new and better evidence that inculpates Assad, I see no reason why the government should not lay a new motion before Parliament, inviting British participation.</p> </blockquote> </div> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/416301924|2013-09-02T21:32:47Z|0117263fdd8241d690e25615f20fa31ab60e46ea -->",
