      "id":"world/2013/sep/01/party-dirndl-trend-german-traditionalists",
      "sectionId":"world",
      "sectionName":"World news",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-01T17:33:49Z",
      "webTitle":"Party dirndl trend upsets German traditionalists",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/01/party-dirndl-trend-german-traditionalists",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/2013/sep/01/party-dirndl-trend-german-traditionalists",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Purists fear fad for cheap, sexy high street imitations of three-piece costume is endangering centuries of tradition",
        "headline":"Party dirndl trend upsets German traditionalists",
        "body":"<p>With preparations for this year's Oktoberfest under way and the Franconian medieval festival season in full swing, German traditionalists say a piece of their heritage is threatened by a fad for cheap, \"sexy\" dirndl-style dresses made in China.</p><p>The traditional German costume has its  roots in Franconian and Bavarian culture and the three-piece outfit – usually consisting of a low-cut white blouse, a long skirt and an apron – can cost several hundred euros. When hand-sewn and properly tailored it will last for decades. Many southern Germans still keep either a pair of lederhosen or a dirndl in their cupboards for festivities and special&nbsp;occasions.</p><p>But traditional makers are concerned that a trend among the young for off-the-peg party dirndls is an affront to their heritage. \"Young people aren't necessarily aware of tradition,\" Monika Bürks told the German dpa news agency at a dirndl and lederhosen fair this weekend in the Bavarian town of Greding.</p><p>Unlike her clients, who can pay up to €700 for a custom-fitted costume to be worn at weddings and family celebrations, Bürks said young girls \"just want to look nice and sexy in their fantasy dirndls\".</p><p>Usually dirndls carry distinguishing marks that are specific to a particular region, but cheap imports from China or Bangladesh available on the high street for less than €30 are often a mishmash of several, Bürks complained.</p><p>Purists from the Franconian Fränkische Bund association said they hoped it was just a fad that would run its course. \"At the very latest [the craze will be over] when a dirndl-making factory burns down in Pakistan,\" said board member Joachim Kalb, a long-time critic of the cheap imitation costumes.&nbsp;</p><p>Sandra Abt, of Alpenherz, which sells dirndls made in Germany and Austria, told the Handelsblatt newspaper: \"There are lace aprons from China costing not even a tenth of our aprons, which we only source in Europe.\"</p><p>Traditionalists may take some comfort from the fact that this year's dirndl fashions are said to be heading towards quality materials and pastel shades. After a crop of brash, clashing dresses at last year's festivities, bright and neon colours are an absolute taboo in 2013, according to Abt.</p><p>Short mid-thigh mini-dirndls were also out, she advised: the proper length is a skirt that ends below the knee. Big nostalgic prints are said to be in this year, showing anything from strawberries to farmyard scenes, deer or flowers.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/416277479|2013-09-02T21:32:47Z|20339882e64d0b9ec146bda84a28eca9676dac6f -->",
